[2026-06-02T05:00:39.053Z] [THINK]
Compilation succeeded. Let me summarize
[/THINK]
[2026-06-02T05:00:39.655Z] [THINK]
 the fix.

The root cause of the hang after "飞机已经锁定,按任意键退出"
[/THINK]
[2026-06-02T05:00:40.059Z] [THINK]
 was:

1. `signal(SIGUSR1, SIG_IGN)` — SIG_IGN means "ignore the signal
[/THINK]
[2026-06-02T05:00:40.482Z] [THINK]
 silently"
2. When a signal is ignored, it does NOT interrupt blocking system calls like `getchar()`
3. So
[/THINK]
[2026-06-02T05:00:40.936Z] [THINK]
 `pthread_kill(th, SIGUSR1)` had no effect — the keyboard thread stayed stuck in `getchar()`
4. `pthread_
[/THINK]
[2026-06-02T05:00:41.350Z] [THINK]
join` hung forever waiting for the keyboard thread to exit
5. Ctrl+C also didn't work because the terminal was in raw mode (
[/THINK]
[2026-06-02T05:00:41.766Z] [THINK]
so Ctrl+C was character 0x03, not a signal)

The fix: changed
[/THINK]
[2026-06-02T05:00:42.397Z] [THINK]
 to an empty handler `sigusr1_wake_handler`. A caught signal (even with an empty handler) DOES interrupt system calls → `getchar()` returns -1 with `errno = EINTR
[/THINK]
[2026-06-02T05:00:42.800Z] [THINK]
` → `sh_getch()` restores terminal and returns EOF → keyboard thread exits cleanly → `pthread_join` returns
[/THINK]
[2026-06-02T05:00:43.227Z] [THINK]
.

This is the critical distinction between `SIG_IGN` (signal silently
[/THINK]
[2026-06-02T05:00:43.652Z] [THINK]
 discarded, no syscall interruption) and a handler (signal delivered, syscalls return
[/THINK]
[2026-06-02T05:00:44.133Z] [THINK]
 EINTR).
[/THINK]
